Additionally, after computing `snapResult`, dispatch it into toolState so the viewport can show the indicator:

```javascript
editorDispatch({
  type: 'UPDATE_TOOL_STATE',
  payload: {
    ...existingPayload,
    snapResult: snapResult,  // NEW: for overlay rendering
  },
});
```

#### 8.3 `selectHandler3d.js` Changes

During drag (line 82-146), replace grid snapping of the delta with smart snapping of the target position:

```javascript
// Instead of snapping the delta, snap the destination position
const inferencePoints = inferenceCache.getPoints(project.parts, toolState.dragPartId);
// excludePartId prevents the dragged part from snapping to itself

const targetPos = {
  x: part.position.x + domainDelta.dx,
  y: part.position.y + domainDelta.dy,
  z: part.position.z + domainDelta.dz,
};

if (snapEnabled) {
  const snapResult = smartSnap3d(targetPos, {
    inferencePoints,
    gridSize: SKETCH_GRID_MINOR,
    camera: viewport?.getCamera?.(),
    domElement: viewport?.getDomElement?.(),
  });
  pos = snapResult.point;
  editorDispatch({ type: 'UPDATE_TOOL_STATE', payload: { snapResult } });
} else {
  pos = targetPos;
}
```

Also, on `onPointerMove` when NOT dragging (hover), detect the hovered face for the face highlight overlay:

```javascript
// In a new hover-handling code path (when e.buttons === 0):
if (intersection?.partId && intersection?.faceNormal) {
  const faceId = identifyFace(intersection.faceNormal);
  editorDispatch({
    type: 'UPDATE_TOOL_STATE',
    payload: { hoverPartId: intersection.partId, hoverFaceId: faceId },
  });
}
```

**Important:** The current `handlePointerMove` in `SketchViewport.jsx` (line 337-344) has a guard that skips pointer-move events when not in a tool interaction (`if (e.buttons === 0 && !toolState.dragging && !toolState.drawing && !toolState.extruding) return;`). This guard must be relaxed to allow hover detection. Change it to always call the handler on move but let handlers decide what to do. Alternatively, add a separate `onHover` method to the handler interface.

I recommend the separate `onHover` method approach, to keep the handler pattern clean:

```javascript
// In SketchViewport.jsx handlePointerMove:
const handlePointerMove = useCallback((e) => {
  const intersection = raycast(e);
  if (!intersection) return;

  // Always call hover for snap indicators
  if (tool.onHover) {
    tool.onHover(intersection, e, toolState, viewportRef.current);
  }

  // Only call onPointerMove during active interaction
  if (e.buttons !== 0 || toolState.dragging || toolState.drawing || toolState.extruding) {
    tool.onPointerMove(intersection, e, toolState, viewportRef.current);
  }
}, [raycast, tool, toolState]);
```

Each handler implements `onHover` to update snap indicators and face highlights. For performance, raycasting on every mouse move is already happening for any active interaction; for hover-only, we are adding raycasting on idle mouse moves. This is fine since Three.js raycasting against ~50 boxes is extremely fast.

#### 8.4 `pushPullHandler3d.js` Changes

The push/pull handler snaps the extrusion distance (a scalar), not a 3D point. The inference engine can still help here: snap the extruded end position to inference points from other parts. For example, extruding a shelf outward should snap to the depth of an adjacent shelf.

```javascript
// In onPointerMove, after computing raw distance:
if (snapEnabled) {
  // Compute the end-face center position at current distance
  const endPoint = computeExtrusionEndCenter(toolState.sourcePart, toolState.faceId, distance);
  const inferencePoints = inferenceCache.getPoints(project.parts, toolState.sourcePart.id);

  // Only snap along the extrusion axis
  const axis = faceIdToAxis(toolState.faceId); // '+z' -> 'z', etc.
  const axisResult = findNearestOnAxis(endPoint, inferencePoints, axis, thresholdMm);

  if (axisResult) {
    distance = axisResult.adjustedDistance;
  } else {
    distance = snapToGrid(distance, SKETCH_GRID_MINOR);
  }
}
```

The `findNearestOnAxis` helper would be a new function in `inferenceEngine.js` that only compares coordinates along a single axis.

---

### 9. `SketchViewport.jsx` Integration

The viewport component orchestrates everything. Changes:

**A. Create and manage SnapOverlay:**

```javascript
// In the initialization useEffect (line 69):
const snapOverlay = createSnapOverlay();
snapOverlayRef.current = snapOverlay;

// Add to root in the scene-rebuild useEffect (line 126):
if (snapOverlayRef.current) {
  root.add(snapOverlayRef.current.group);
}

// Dispose in cleanup
```

**B. Create inference cache:**

```javascript
const inferenceCacheRef = useRef(createInferenceCache());
```

**C. Pass cache and viewport to handler factory:**

In the `useMemo` at line 48-60, add `inferenceCache: inferenceCacheRef.current` and pass `viewportRef` through the context.

**D. Update overlay from toolState:**

```javascript
// New useEffect watching toolState.snapResult:
useEffect(() => {
  const overlay = snapOverlayRef.current;
  if (!overlay) return;

  if (toolState.snapResult?.snapped) {
    overlay.updateSnapIndicator(toolState.snapResult);
  } else {
    overlay.clear();
  }
}, [toolState.snapResult]);

// New useEffect watching toolState.hoverPartId/hoverFaceId:
useEffect(() => {
  const overlay = snapOverlayRef.current;
  if (!overlay) return;

  if (toolState.hoverPartId && toolState.hoverFaceId) {
    const part = project.parts.find(p => p.id === toolState.hoverPartId);
    if (part) {
      overlay.updateHoverFace(part, toolState.hoverFaceId);
    }
  } else {
    overlay.updateHoverFace(null, null);
  }
}, [toolState.hoverPartId, toolState.hoverFaceId, project.parts]);
```

**E. Exclude overlay from raycasting:**

Add `'SnapOverlay'` to the `isOverlayObject` check (line 543-552):

```javascript
function isOverlayObject(obj) {
  let current = obj;
  while (current) {
    if (current.name === 'DrawingPlaneOverlay' || current.name === 'ExtrusionPreview' ||
        current.name === 'PlaneGrid' || current.name === 'DrawPreview' ||
        current.name === 'SnapOverlay') {
      return true;
    }
    current = current.parent;
  }
  return false;
}
```

**F. Update status bar to show snap type:**

In the status bar JSX (line 517-528), add snap type indicator:

```jsx
{toolState.snapResult?.snapped && (
  <span className={styles.statusSnap}>
    Snap: {toolState.snapResult.inference.type}
  </span>
)}
```

---

### 10. Auto-Constraint Suggestion (Future Enhancement, Minimal Scaffolding Now)

When a part is placed at an inference point that belongs to another part, the system could auto-suggest a constraint. For the initial implementation, I recommend adding this as a post-placement toast notification rather than auto-creating constraints, to avoid unexpected behavior.

In `drawRectHandler3d.js`'s `onPointerUp`, after creating the part:

```javascript
if (toolState.snapResult?.snapped && toolState.snapResult.inference.partId) {
  editorDispatch({
    type: 'SET_STATUS_MESSAGE',
    message: `Placed at ${toolState.snapResult.inference.type} of existing part`,
  });
}
```

A more sophisticated version (Phase 2) would call `createConstraint` with appropriate anchor mappings derived from the inference point's `faceId` and the new part's placement position.

---

### 11. Implementation Sequence

**Phase 1 (Core, 4 files):**
1. Create `partGeometry.js` -- pure geometry extraction functions
2. Create `inferenceEngine.js` -- snap logic, nearest-neighbor, threshold computation
3. Modify `snap.js` -- add `smartSnap3d`
4. Create `inferenceCache.js` -- simple memoization wrapper

**Phase 2 (Visual, 2 files):**
5. Create `SnapOverlay.js` -- Three.js visual indicators
6. Modify `SketchViewport.jsx` -- wire overlay creation, lifecycle, raycasting exclusion

**Phase 3 (Integration, 4 files):**
7. Modify `handlers3d/index.js` -- pass inference context
8. Modify `drawRectHandler3d.js` -- use smartSnap3d
9. Modify `selectHandler3d.js` -- use smartSnap3d + hover face detection
10. Modify `pushPullHandler3d.js` -- use axis-constrained inference snap

**Phase 4 (Cleanup, 3 files):**
11. Replace duplicated `getPartDimensions` in `drawingPlane.js`, `extrusion.js`, and `ExtrusionPreview.js` with imports from `partGeometry.js`

---

### 12. Key Design Decisions and Trade-offs

**Why pure functions for inference, not Three.js raycasting of edges?**
Three.js can raycast against `EdgesGeometry` to find exact edge hover. However, this couples snap logic to the rendering layer and makes testing harder. The pure-function approach computes corners/midpoints from domain models, which is simpler, testable, and works regardless of how the 3D scene is structured. The ~1mm inaccuracy from using bounding-box geometry (vs. actual mesh edges) is irrelevant for furniture dimensioning.

**Why screen-space threshold?**
A fixed world-space threshold (e.g., 30mm) would feel different at different zoom levels. At wide zoom, 30mm is tiny and hard to trigger. At close zoom, it is large and captures unintended snaps. The screen-space approach (15px) provides consistent UX.

**Why not use a spatial index (k-d tree)?**
With fewer than 2000 inference points in the worst case, linear scan takes microseconds. A spatial index adds complexity for no measurable benefit in this domain.

**Why a separate `onHover` handler method?**
The existing pattern has `onPointerMove` only called during active interactions (drag/draw/extrude). Adding hover detection to `onPointerMove` would either require removing the performance guard or overloading the method's semantics. A separate `onHover` keeps responsibilities clear and the performance guard intact.

**Coordinate system handling:**
The inference engine works entirely in domain coordinates (x, y, z where z is vertical). The `SnapOverlay` converts to Three.js coordinates (x, z_domain, y_domain) only at the rendering boundary, using the same pattern as `DrawingPlaneOverlay.planeToThree` and `buildSketchPreview.createPanelMesh`. This keeps the core logic clean.

